# Project context
You are working in a React + TypeScript prototype that mimics a Dynamics 365 (model-driven) app
for internal Marine Management Organisation staff.

Design system:
- Fluent UI v8 + v9 — prefer v9 for new components, tables, and menus.
- ListView.tsx uses Fluent UI v9 Table.
- Use Fluent UI v9 Popover/Menu for header and cell hover menus (see ListView.tsx Title hover menu pattern).

Layout & Navigation:
- Layout: TopBar (navy header) ▸ Custom Left Nav rail ▸ Main content.
- Navigation: custom Nav.tsx with Nav.css styled to match D365 (expandable sections, chevrons, spacing).
- Data: mocked JSON in src/mock-data; entity configs in src/config/entities.

Styling:
- Use CSS files per component (e.g. Nav.css) or Fluent v9 makeStyles/mergeClasses.
- No external CSS frameworks.

---

# Coding conventions
- Functional components + hooks only.
- Import types with `import type { … } from '@fluentui/react'`.
- Assume `initializeIcons()` runs in `src/main.tsx`.
- Keep row components small (e.g. ListView.tsx, RecordForm.tsx).
- Use Fluent v9 `makeStyles`/`mergeClasses` for styling.
- Tables: set fixed/min/max widths for key columns to match D365 layout.
- Header menus: narrow popover (≈180–220px), chevron immediately after label, no left padding, bold label, open on click.
- Colour tokens: #0078d4 active, #edebe9 hover, #f3f2f1 rail background.

---

# New page / entity scaffold checklist
1. Add mock rows → `src/mock-data/<entityPlural>.json`
2. Describe columns + form layout → `src/config/entities/<entity>.json`
3. Create `<Entity>ListView.tsx` in `src/components` (Fluent v9 Table)
4. Register a left-nav link in `Shell.tsx` groups array
5. Add a route + page stub in `App.tsx` (or your router)
6. Keep each PR focussed on one entity/page

---

# File & folder structure
- Components → `src/components` using PascalCase filenames
- Non-React helpers → `src/utils`
- Use relative imports (no absolute aliases here)

---

# Allowed libraries
Allowed: `@fluentui/*`, `date-fns`, `uuid`, `faker`  
Avoid: `moment`, `lodash` (poor tree-shaking), any CSS-in-JS besides Fluent v9 utilities

---

# Navigation component rules (D365 styling)
- Use custom `Nav.tsx` (not Fluent Nav) for precise D365 look
- `Nav.css` handles expand/collapse, chevrons, hover states
- Chevrons: down (V) when closed, up (^) when expanded
- Selected item = white background + left border #0078d4
- Full-height nav with responsive behaviour

---

# Commit style
Use Conventional Commits:
- feat: …  (new screens/components)
- fix: …   (bug fixes)
- chore: … (tooling / lint / deps)
Keep PRs under ~300 lines where possible